My wife broke the presser foot lifter ever on her serger. She wasn't the first one this one had alredy been glued together once by the previous owner. I got out my calipers measured it up and made a "good enough" model. It doesn't have a thread cutter in it but it does fit and does work properly. The sewing places want ~$20 US for this part when a few cents worth of plastic and a few mintutes will do the trick. Replaces Elna Serger Presser Bar Lifter (Part #396014-76) Compatible with Elna Serger (Overlock) Models:
604E, 614DE, 624DS, 624DSE,704DEX, 744, 745, 845, 904DCX, 905DCX, 925DCX, 945, PRO4DC, PRO4DE, PRO5DC & PRO5DE. Alternative Part Numbers Include 396010-85

Print part and affix to the serger where the original lever broke off.  
If you do not have a 3d printer and need this part please feel free to contact me and I'll print one out for you. All you have to do is pay shipping and a small fee for the plastic.

A version of my model "To revive a unicorn" with the upper part of the skull being hollow. I used it as a bird feeder :) The model is part of a project which explore 3D-printings ability to make art accessible to everyone, everywhere and become an everyday-experience,
as well as its capability to let people rework and remix art and find new purposes and contexts for art pieces. As part of the project I want to encourage you and everyone else to use this model in whatever way you can imagine - Remix it, hack it or just print it and use it as it is, for what you want. And I will highly appreciate you sharing photos, models and other documentation of what you might do whith it, both here and and on Instagram with the hastag #toreviveaunicorn. Thanks :)
This model was printed on a xyz da vinci AiO in the maximum size, with the standard xyz-software. I think it has to be quite large for the birds to get their heads through the eye sockets.

I made the tensioner shorter and wider, and made the backing plate with end tabs and protrusions to keep it in place on the axis mount. It reuses the ball bearings, and screws and nut, but requires an additional nylock nut, and square nut which are not used in the stock configuration.

Put the backing plate on the original long screw, using a new m3 nylock nut. Leave the nut just loose enough so the screw will turn in the plate. The nylock nut's purpose it to just hold the screw in position.
You will need to put a new m3 square nut in the tensioner, and it requires a fair bit of force to seat it low enough.

title: Thing10
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This was inspired by nicholasclewis's photo of his glowing Gold Star here: http://www.thingiverse.com/derivative:4360 . It really made me want to design a glowing, pointy, handheld object, especially since most of my designs aren't really meant to be handled. So, this is the result! Thing10 is printed in two identical halves, which can be glued together to form a rough sphere, or enjoyed on their own. The printed half is vaguely reminiscent of the Sydney Opera House crossed with a sea urchin. I may have gotten carried away with the pointiness. The walls are designed to be a single filament wide. I use 0.3mm layers, with width/thickness ratio of 2.0, giving a wall width of 0.6mm. If your wall width is different, you may want to scale the STL file. You probably want to preview the build in software, like with Skeinlayer in Skeinforge. In general, Skeinforge seems to be pretty finicky with very thin walls. I suggest printing multiple copies at the same time, like 2 or 4, to allow some cooling, since it is a very quick print. If you are having trouble printing Thing10 at the default size, you could try scaling it up 2x (or whatever gives you double filament walls). I plan to try this soon since a big one would let you see the details better. As for the glowing, options include fluorescent or glow-in-the-dark filament, or those types of paint applied afterwards. I designed Thing10 so it could be painted from the bottom (when printed in clear PLA), so that you don't rub off paint when playing with it. I used this technique with some glow-in-the-dark paint for the green one in the picture. The blue one is Ultimachine's translucent blue PLA. Obviously it is much easier to paint the two halves before gluing them together. Dimensions:
Thing 10: 35.7mm diameter x 15.66mm tall (each half)
Thing 10b: 71.4mm diameter x 31.31mm tall (each half) Update 5-09-2011: I printed it out at double the size and it is much more impressive. I've uploaded Thing10b.stl which is just the original file linearly scaled by 2x. I recommend this larger version, and it is still pretty quick to print.

My wife and mother-in-law got a little tired of always taking their cases off to use their tripod mount; now you can use nearly ANY phone (even phablets!) in nearly ANY case on your tripod without a specific mount case.

Thanks to cswaim to his UPTM; I was inspired by his clamping method, and thought it could be made a little more universal and secure with a wider clamping surface and tightening nuts.    
Should print in 3.5-4 hrs on standard settings without support.  Optimized for PLA.

1x 1/4"/20 Nut
2x 1/4"/20 Wingnuts
Felt or rubber padding. Print both top and bottom. Place nut in bottom center hex indentation, glue in place with hotglue at the TOP of the nut. Thread your bolts through the bottom holes, place a dab of hotglue on bottom of the hexhead face, press into place. Cut some felt or rubber self-adhesive pads and place them on the outsides of the phone mount angles. See picture. Mount onto your favorite tripod, monopod, or gorillapod.

description.text:

I printed this in two sections, there is the body and there is the right arm.  I just glued them together with super glue; a better joint could have been modeled but I was just getting fed up with the software.  
Overall printing this 320cm tall statue took about 700g of plastic.

You need five pins, five clicker and two decoshapes. The other parts only have to be printed once. If you want to paint the cryptex, do this before assembly! At first take the outer_tube and take one clicker. Fit the clicker into the first recess and press it down with a flat screwdriver. At the same time slide the fist letterring (C) over the clicker till it is flush to the outer tube. Repeat this process for all letterings (c,r,y,p,t) and take some superglue to fit the end piece over the outer tube to fix all. The second part ist the assembly of the inner tube. Take the inner_tube and fit the pins into the holes. Take some superglue to fix them, if this is necessary.
the last part is glueing the deco_shapes on the flat front sides of the outer- and the inner-tube. Make the antique look:
At first you have to color the cryptex completely in gold. After the color is dry, you take a old cloth, lay it down and make some lays. Now carefully put some black high fluent color on it. The last thing you have to do is to roll the Cryptex over that cloth. After some trials you can find out the right dose of color. Now your finished. Please tell me your experiences.

Building a prob but I want to keep things unsoldered so I can tweak it from time to time. The big issue is that the smallest breadboard I can get is still to big to fit in the prop. Found someone on thingiverse that shows that it's possible to create you're own breadboards.  
So I modeled a custom breadboard for my project, printed it out, filled it with aluminum and it seems to do the job. The only issue is that you can't just keep plugging / unplugging the same spot since it wears out quickly and makes the connection pretty loose. Other then that, putting in aluminum is a pain.  
I wish there was a way to easily make breadboard bits that can be interconnected to create any size or shape a project can use. In my head I can see how it works, the only big issue is printing out the plastic bits and have the right internals to make the connections reliable like real breadboards.

comments.text: I am amazed how well this works. I suspected that the Al foil would have high resistance but Its only the order of 2-3 ohm which is completely acceptable.

  • The hands (made them a bit wider & set them higher, more correct to the official character models)
  • The feet (made them a bit taller, more correct to voxelous version)
  • The face (adding eyebrows and a cheek effect to show off the smile.)
  • Added some eyes to fill in if you have some black ABS to use
